    <fr:title text="Modulus of complex number">Modulus of complex number</fr:title>
    <fr:taxon>definition</fr:taxon>
    <fr:meta name="source"><fr:link href="/lankham-2016-linear/" title="Linear algebra as an introduction to abstract mathematics" uri="http://localhost:8000/lankham-2016-linear/" display-uri="lankham-2016-linear" type="local">Linear algebra as an introduction to abstract mathematics</fr:link> Definition 2.2.10</fr:meta>
    <fr:meta name="source"><fr:link href="/axler-1996-linear/" title="Linear Algebra Done Right" uri="http://localhost:8000/axler-1996-linear/" display-uri="axler-1996-linear" type="local">Linear Algebra Done Right</fr:link> Definition 4.2</fr:meta>
  </fr:frontmatter>
  <fr:mainmatter>
    <html:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[z=x+\mathrm {i} y]]></fr:tex> be a complex number with <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x,y\in \mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex>. We define the <html:dfn>Modulus</html:dfn> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[z]]></fr:tex> to be the value <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[|z|=\sqrt {x^{2}+y^{2}}>0]]></fr:tex>. In particular, if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x\in \mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex>, then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[|x+\mathrm {i} 0|=\sqrt {x^{2}+0}=|x|]]></fr:tex> is just the absolute value.</html:p>
  </fr:mainmatter>
