                <fr:title text="Set of complex numbers">Set of complex numbers</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>definition</fr:taxon>
                <fr:meta name="source"><fr:link href="/lankham-2016-linear/" title="Linear algebra as an introduction to abstract mathematics" uri="http://localhost:8000/lankham-2016-linear/" display-uri="lankham-2016-linear" type="local">Linear algebra as an introduction to abstract mathematics</fr:link> §2.1</fr:meta>
                <fr:meta name="source"><fr:link href="/axler-1996-linear/" title="Linear Algebra Done Right" uri="http://localhost:8000/axler-1996-linear/" display-uri="axler-1996-linear" type="local">Linear Algebra Done Right</fr:link> 1.1</fr:meta>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter>
                <html:p>We define the <html:dfn>Set of Complex Numbers</html:dfn> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {C}=\{(x,y)\mid  x,y\in \mathbb {R}\}]]></fr:tex>. Given a complex number <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[z=(x,y)]]></fr:tex>, we call <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Re (z)=x]]></fr:tex> the <html:dfn>Real Part</html:dfn> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[z]]></fr:tex>, and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\Im (z)=y]]></fr:tex> the <html:dfn>Imaginary Part</html:dfn> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[z]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
                <html:p>We write <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {i}=(0,1)]]></fr:tex> for the <html:dfn>Imaginary Unit</html:dfn> and write <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[z=(x,y)]]></fr:tex> as <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[z=x+\mathrm {i} y]]></fr:tex>. (Electrical Engineers use <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[j]]></fr:tex> instead for the imaginary unit.)</html:p>
              </fr:mainmatter>
