                <fr:title text="Multiplicative inverse of complex numbers">Multiplicative inverse of complex numbers</fr:title>
                <fr:taxon>theorem</fr:taxon>
                <fr:meta name="source"><fr:link href="/lankham-2016-linear/" title="Linear algebra as an introduction to abstract mathematics" uri="http://localhost:8000/lankham-2016-linear/" display-uri="lankham-2016-linear" type="local">Linear algebra as an introduction to abstract mathematics</fr:link> Theorem 2.2.6</fr:meta>
                <fr:meta name="source"><fr:link href="/axler-1996-linear/" title="Linear Algebra Done Right" uri="http://localhost:8000/axler-1996-linear/" display-uri="axler-1996-linear" type="local">Linear Algebra Done Right</fr:link> Definition 1.5</fr:meta>
              </fr:frontmatter>
              <fr:mainmatter><html:p>For any nonzero <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[z\in \mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[z\neq 0]]></fr:tex>, there exists a unique complex number denoted <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[z^{-1}]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[zz^{-1}=1]]></fr:tex>. Moreover, if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[z=x+\mathrm {i} y]]></fr:tex> with <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x,y\in \mathbb {R}]]></fr:tex>, then
<fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[z^{-1}=\frac {x}{x^{2}+y^{2}}+\mathrm {i}\frac {-y}{x^{2}+y^{2}}]]></fr:tex></html:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link href="/alex-nelson/" title="Alex Nelson" uri="http://localhost:8000/alex-nelson/" display-uri="alex-nelson" type="local">Alex Nelson</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>12</fr:month><fr:day>9</fr:day></fr:date><fr:taxon>proof</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><html:p><html:strong>Uniqueness:</html:strong> Suppose there are two complex numbers <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[w\in \mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v\in \mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[zv=1]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[zw=1]]></fr:tex>. Then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v=1v=(zw)v=(wz)v=w(zv)=w1=w]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
<html:p><html:strong>Existence:</html:strong> Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[z=x+\mathrm {i} y]]></fr:tex>. We see <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x^{2}+y^{2}>0]]></fr:tex> is nonzero, so the complex number
<fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[w=\frac {x}{x^{2}+y^{2}}+\mathrm {i}\frac {-y}{x^{2}+y^{2}}]]></fr:tex>
is well-defined. We just need to check <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[zw=1]]></fr:tex>, but the trick is <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[(x+\mathrm {i} y)(x-\mathrm {i} y)=x^{2}+y^{2}]]></fr:tex> and the result follows immediately.</html:p><html:span class="qed">∎</html:span></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
</fr:mainmatter>
